# Development Workflow Guide

## Available Scripts

### Monorepo-level (run from root)
- `pnpm dev`: Start all apps in dev mode via Turbo
- `pnpm build`: Build all apps via Turbo
- `pnpm lint`: Lint all apps via Turbo
- `pnpm format`: Format all apps via Turbo
- `pnpm typecheck`: Type-check all apps via Turbo

### Web app (run from root with filter)
- `pnpm --filter @repo/web dev`: Start development server
- `pnpm --filter @repo/web build`: Build the application
- `pnpm --filter @repo/web start`: Start production server
- `pnpm --filter @repo/web lint`: Run Biome linter
- `pnpm --filter @repo/web format`: Format code with Biome
- `pnpm --filter @repo/web content`: Generate Fumadocs MDX content
- `pnpm --filter @repo/web db:generate`: Generate new migration files based on schema changes
- `pnpm --filter @repo/web db:migrate`: Apply pending migrations to the database
- `pnpm --filter @repo/web db:push`: Sync schema changes directly to the database (development only)
- `pnpm --filter @repo/web db:studio`: Open Drizzle Studio for database inspection and management
- `pnpm --filter @repo/web email`: Start email template development server

### Shortcut scripts (root)
- `pnpm web:dev`: Same as `pnpm --filter @repo/web dev`
- `pnpm web:build`: Same as `pnpm --filter @repo/web build`
- `pnpm web:content`: Same as `pnpm --filter @repo/web content`
- `pnpm web:db:generate`: Same as `pnpm --filter @repo/web db:generate`

## Development Process
1. Use TypeScript for all new code
2. Follow Biome formatting rules
3. Write server actions in `apps/web/src/actions/`
4. Use Zustand for client-side state
5. Implement database changes through Drizzle migrations
6. Use Radix UI components for consistent UI
7. Follow the established directory structure
8. Write tests for new features
9. Update content collections when adding new content
10. Use environment variables from `env.example`

## Code Style
- Use functional components with hooks
- Implement proper error handling
- Follow TypeScript best practices
- Use proper type definitions
- Document complex logic
- Keep components small and focused
- Use proper naming conventions
